We heard a lot of soundbites last night. President Donald J. Trump, yet again, vowed to repeal and replace the Affordable Care Act, create countless new jobs and rebuild our crumbling infrastructure. Unfortunately, he provided few details on how he and Congressional Republicans would pursue and enact such sweeping policies. Some seven years after the Affordable Care Act was signed into law, Republicans and the Trump Administration have no comprehensive plan to expand affordable, high-quality healthcare to more people without jeopardizing the livelihood of more than 22 million newly-insured Americans. Moreover, I heard nothing remotely resembling a ‚Äòjobs plan,‚Äô and on investing in infrastructure‚Äîa proposal Democrats have fought for for the last decade‚Äîit remains to be seen if the very same Republicans who refused to increase infrastructure funding for years are now prepared to do an about-face. #JointSession

DON'T FORGET - House Republicans are forcing a vote on the #WrongCHOICEAct today, a bill to deregulate our financial system--putting us right back to where we were BEFORE the 2008 Financial Crisis-- and gutting the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau (CFPB), which has saved Americans $12 BILLION to date.

I voted against the Financial CHOICE Act because it is the wrong choice for consumers, investors, and our economy. Instead of gutting consumer and investor financial protections, as this partisan bill would do, Congress needs to work in a bipartisan fashion to build on Dodd-Frank‚Äôs successes and improve on its shortcomings to keep our economy moving forward. Repealing Dodd-Frank and eliminating the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau‚Äîwhich in just six years has recovered almost $12 billion for more than 29 million Americans‚Äîdoes the exact opposite, threatening the progress our economy has made since the 2008 Financial Crisis.  This bill is the wrong choice for America.
